== CLAIM UNDER VERIFICATION ==
Refutation of Conjecture A.13 of arXiv:2412.16177v1, by counterexample
G = A5 x S3 (order 360), x = ((0 1 2 3 4), id).

== STATEMENT PROVENANCE ==
Source: "Mining Math Conjectures from LLMs: A Pruning Approach",
Jake Chuharski, Elias Rojas Collins, Mark Meringolo. arXiv:2412.16177 (only one
version, v1, Mon 9 Dec 2024). PDF fetched 2026-06-11 from
https://arxiv.org/pdf/2412.16177v1 (saved as paper-2412.16177v1.pdf, 1,030,052 bytes);
HTML cross-checked at https://arxiv.org/html/2412.16177v1 (the {conj} environments fail
to render in HTML, so the A.13 numbering is only visible in the PDF).

Verbatim from PDF (appendix p.60, section A.5.6 "Additional Conjectures", whose
preamble reads "The following conjectures are just a couple of the conjectures that had
code that was unable to be run but are still potentially interesting from Claude:"):

  Conjecture A.13. Let G be a non-solvable group. For any element x in G, if SolG(x)
  is a proper subgroup of G, then the intersection of SolG(x) with all of its
  conjugates in G is always contained in the hypercenter of G.

Definition 3.1 (verbatim): "Let G be a finite group. For any element x in G, the
solubilizer of x in G is defined as: SolG(x) := {y in G | <x, y> is soluble}".
The word "hypercenter" occurs nowhere else in the paper and is never defined, so the
standard meaning applies: Z_inf(G), the stable term of the upper central series.

Statement fidelity vs refuted-claims.json: EXACT MATCH (character-for-character),
including the "code was unable to be run" provenance note.

== INDEPENDENT RECOMPUTATION (checker_a13.py, exact arithmetic only) ==
Group model: permutations of {0..7}; A5 = even perms of {0..4}, S3 = perms of {5,6,7};
360 elements, full 360x360 multiplication table, all products verified to stay in G.

(1) G non-solvable: derived series orders 360 -> 180 -> 60, stabilizing at a perfect
    subgroup of order 60 (A5 x 1). G is finite, satisfying Definition 3.1's scope.
(2) Sol_G(x) for x = ((0 1 2 3 4), id): order 60; verified CLOSED under multiplication
    (a genuine subgroup, so A.13's hypothesis applies); proper (60 < 360); product
    shape (order-10 subgroup of A5, i.e. D10 = N_A5(<x>)) x S3 confirmed via
    projections (|proj_A5| = 10, |proj_S3| = 6, 10*6 = 60).
(3) Normal core = intersection over ALL 360 g of g^-1 Sol_G(x) g: order 6, equal to
    1 x S3 (every element fixes points 0..4), verified normal in G and solvable.
(4) Upper central series: Z_0 = 1 is already stable (Z(G) = 1), so the hypercenter
    Z_inf(G) = 1 (order 1).
(5) Core (order 6) is NOT contained in the hypercenter (order 1); witness element
    (id, (6 7)) = [0,1,2,3,4,5,7,6].  ==> CONJECTURE A.13 IS FALSE.

== EXTENSION FINDINGS (full brute-force sweep over all 360 x in G) ==
- |Sol_G(x)| distribution over all x: {60: 144 elements, 144: 120, 216: 90, 360: 6}.
- Sol_G(x) is a subgroup for exactly 150 of 360 x: the 6 x in 1 x S3 (where
  Sol = G, not proper) and the 144 x = (5-cycle, anything) (where Sol is proper,
  order 60). The size-144 and size-216 solubilizers are not subgroups (consistent
  with Lagrange: neither 144 nor 216 divides 360).
- For ALL 144 x with Sol_G(x) a proper subgroup, the normal core contains 1 x S3 and
  hence is NOT contained in the (trivial) hypercenter: A.13 fails at every applicable
  x of this G, not just the certificate element.
- Structural reason confirmed computationally: the solvable normal subgroup 1 x S3
  lies inside Sol_G(x) for EVERY x in G, hence inside every conjugate of every
  solubilizer, hence inside every core.
- Reading-equivalence confirmed: Sol_G(x^g) = g^-1 Sol_G(x) g for the certificate x
  and ALL 360 g, so the two grammatical readings of "its conjugates" (conjugates of
  the set Sol_G(x) vs solubilizers of conjugates of x) define the same intersection.

